==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr}} {{term|hélicoptère|lang=fr}}, from {{etyl|el}} {{term|ελικόπτερον|sc=Grek|tr=helikopteron|lang=el}}, from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|έλιξ|sc=polytonic|tr=helix|lang=grc}} (genitive {{term|έλικος|sc=polytonic|tr=helikos||turning, revolving, rotating, spinning|lang=grc}}) + {{term|πτερόν|sc=polytonic|tr=pteron||wing; anything winged|lang=grc}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|AusE}} {{IPA|/ˈheliˌkoptə(r)/}}, {{SAMPA|"heli%kopt@(r)/}}
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈhɛl.iˌkɒp.tə(ɹ)/|/ˈhɛl.ɪˌkɒp.tə(ɹ)/}}; {{SAMPA|/"hEl.i%kQp.t@(r)|/"hEl.I%kQp.t@(r)/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈhɛlɪˌkɔptəɻ/}}, {{SAMPA|/"hElI.kOpt@r\`/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An aircraft that is borne along by one or more sets of long rotating blades which allow it to hover, move in any direction including [[reverse]], or land; and having a smaller set of blades on its tail that stabilize the aircraft.
#: ''We flew over the city in a '''helicopter'''''.
# a powered [[trowel]]ing machine with spinning blades used to spread [[concrete]].

